properties.name: Peak's Addition
properties.description: Peak's Addition, formerly known as Mill Creek, was first subdivided in 1897, and was the first neighborhood in the former city of East Dallas to experience development. It takes its name from the creek (covered in the 1930s) that used to run through the area and the industry along it. The western portion of the neighborhood was designated the Peak’s Suburban Addition Historic District in 1997.

properties.name: Kleberg
properties.description: Located in the most southeastern portion of the city, about 15 miles from the city center, Kleberg is a “bedroom community” neighborhood that exhibits rural character while still remaining within the city limits. Originally its own incorporated town, it was consolidated with Dallas in 1978.

properties.name: Northaven Park
properties.description: Established in 1955, Northaven Park is a neighborhood of around 1200 homes. Residents enjoy a natural creek and two parks within the neighborhood’s one-square mile. The Northaven Park Neighborhood Association (NPNA), established in 1996, supports neighborhood events throughout the year and  has an active crime watch team.

properties.name: Brettonwoods
properties.description: Prior to the 1950's the place now known as Brettonwoods was farmland and woods nestled along Crow Creek. Much of Brettonwoods was originally part of the Overton farm. In the early 1950's, the Overton family began to sell tracts of land along the woodlands of Crow Creek and the open farmland to the north of the neighborhood. The winding streets & the towering trees in the southern sector of Oak Cliff is home to a variety of houses built mostly in the 1950's, which include ranches, traditional and mid- century moderns. The Neighborhood started a Nextdoor community in May 2012 and became a Neighborhood Association in September 2014. They hold consistent quarterly meetings and an annually well attended National Night Out event in addition to other neighborhood-based social and service gatherings.

properties.name: Vickery Meadow(s)
properties.description: Vickery Meadow (known to some as 'Vickery Meadows') is the densest neighborhood in Dallas with about 12,000 housing units, primarily in multi-family and apartment residences. Originally intended for young singles, the neighborhood now has a significant immigrant and refugee population. The Vickery Meadow Improvement District was founded in 1993.

properties.name: Monopoly Place
properties.description: Monopoly Place is a small managed neighborhood of duplexes gradually built from the 1940s to 1970s located east of White Rock Lake.

properties.name: Glen Abbey
properties.description: Glen Abbey is a multi-million dollar, 102-home subdivision built on the former estate of Clint Murchison, Sr., developed over the last 20 years.

properties.name: Churchill Way Estates
properties.description: Churchill Way Estates is a neighborhood of homes primarily dating from the 1980s, just south of the LBJ Freeway.

properties.name: Lobello
properties.description: Deed-restricted, one -acre lots for Lobello Estates were first subdivided in the 1940s. The neighborhood, just west of the Dallas North Tollway, includes mid-century and newer homes.

properties.name: Les Jardins Estates
properties.description: Les Jardins Estates is a small neighborhood just north of Preston Hollow. It shares a crime watch with Royal Northaven and Hockaday.

properties.name: Northtown Square
properties.description: Northtown Square is a small neighborhood developed during the 1970s and 80s in the far northwest corner of the city.

properties.name: Light Pointe Place
properties.description: Light Pointe Place is a small neighborhood just north of I-30 on the border with Mesquite built in the 2000s and 2010s.

properties.name: Mayflower Estates
properties.description: A neighborhood of estates just north of Walnut Hill Lane developed in the 1950s by Carr Collins.

properties.name: Northwood Heights
properties.description: Northwood Heights is a very small neighborhood of just four streets developed in the 1970s and 80s.

properties.name: Bent Tree Hills
properties.description: Bent Tree Hills is a subdivision of single family homes and apartments in the very northern tip of the Dallas, just inside the city limits, constructed in the mid-1990s.

properties.name: Churchill Pointe
properties.description: Churchill Pointe is a small gated community developed in the late 1990s, just south of the LBJ Freeway.

properties.name: Emerald Isles
properties.description: Emerald Isles is a small neighborhood of single family homes and apartment buildings dating primarily from the late 1990s and early 2000s on the eastern shore of White Rock Lake.

properties.name: Club Manor
properties.description: Club Manor is a small neighborhood of about 50 homes and apartments developed during the 1970s and 80s located along the western edge of the Dallas Athletic Club, a private country club.

properties.name: Country Brook
properties.description: Established in 1981, Country Brook is a subdivision of 163 homes.

properties.name: Glendale Heights
properties.description: Developed as a post-war brick addition, Glendale Heights is a neighborhood of more than 300 homes just north of E Ledbetter Drive.

properties.name: The Gables at Royal Lane
properties.description: The Gables at Royal Lane is a planned development of townhomes built in 1983-4 in northwest Dallas with Harry Hines Boulevard to the east of the neighborhood.

properties.name: The Downs of Hillcrest
properties.description: The Downs of Hillcrest is a gated community of more than 150 homes primarily developed around 2000 located just south of the LBJ Freeway.

properties.name: Enclave at Grove Hill
properties.description: The Enclave at Grove Hill is a gated community of homes and apartments developed during the late 1960s and early 70s located just south of 1-30 in Buckner Terrace.

properties.name: Hideaway Valley
properties.description: Hideaway Valley is a small neighborhood of approximately 30 homes primarily built in the 1960s located near the Dallas Executive Airport.

properties.name: Encinos Park
properties.description: Encinos Park, sometimes just referred to as Encino, is a small new subdivision off Kiest Boulevard.

properties.name: Fairway Estates
properties.description: Fairway Estates is a small neighborhood located within the Dallas Athletic Club, a private country club in operation since 1919.

properties.name: Oak Lawn
properties.description: A large neighborhood of almost 15 square miles boasting older residences; new development of apartments, condos, and high-rises; and a diverse number of uses. The boundaries were defined by the city’s Oak Lawn Special Purpose District in 1985.

properties.name: Parkway Village
properties.description: Established in 1985, Parkway Village is a planned community of condominiums and single-family homes.

properties.name: Parkdale
properties.description: Established in 1926, the Parkdale neighborhood includes about 1,000 homes dating primarily from the 1950s bordering the Great Trinity Forest in southeast Dallas.

properties.name: Pemberton Hill
properties.description: Pemberton Hill is a predominantly Hispanic neighborhood of approximately 3000 homes and apartments dating primarily from mid-twentieth century on the east bank of the Trinity River in southeast Dallas. The Pemberton Hill Recreation Center is a neighborhood focal point.

properties.name: Pleasant Grove
properties.description: A large neighborhood located between White Rock Creek and the border with Balch Springs, Pleasant Grove was originally settled in the 1840s and annexed in pieces to the City of Dallas between the late 1940s and 1962. Large portions of southeast Dallas are often mistakenly referred to as Pleasant Grove.

properties.name: Highlands Parkway
properties.description: Highlands Parkway is a neighborhood of around 200 homes and apartments developed in the 1980s at the far northwestern city limit.

properties.name: Rylie
properties.description: Located in far southeastern Dallas along a former Southern Pacific Railroad line, the former town of Rylie dates back to the 1870s. Rylie, which includes more than 2000 homes, was incorporated into Dallas in the 1960s.

properties.name: State Thomas
properties.description: Established in 1887, making it one of the oldest residential neighborhoods in the city, State Thomas was originally known as Overand’s Addition. State Thomas is a City of Dallas Landmark District that boasts the largest remaining collection of intact Victorian residential structures in the city.

properties.name: Horizon Estate
properties.description: Horizon Estate is a neighborhood of single family homes and apartments dating primarily from the 1950s and 60s directly south of the Veterans Affairs Hospital.

properties.name: Mountain Ridge
properties.description: Mountain Ridge is a small subdivision in Mountain Creek, first developed in 2003, near Joe Pool Lake.

properties.name: Waterford on the Park
properties.description: Waterford on the Park is a small subdivision of homes primarily built around the turn of the twenty-first century, just south of I-635 and west of the White Rock Creek Trail.

properties.name: North Cliff
properties.description: North Cliff is a residential neighborhood first developed in the 1920s. The neighborhood association formed in 1987, and the neighborhood was designated a conservation district in 1996.

properties.name: Wheatland Meadows
properties.description: Wheatland Meadows is a new subdivision located just inside the city limits.

properties.name: Royal Highlands Village
properties.description: Royal Highlands Village is a small subdivision of about 100 homes developed in the 1970s.

properties.name: White Rock Valley
properties.description: Established in 1948, White Rock Valley is a neighborhood of about 1,700 homes located just north of White Rock Lake.

properties.name: Oak Highlands Estates
properties.description: Oak Highlands Estates is a subdivision of around 150 single-family homes dating from the 1970s and 80s adjacent to Harry Moss Park.

properties.name: Loupot Heights
properties.description: Loupot Heights is a neighborhood of around 300 homes primarily dating from the 1940s and 50s near DART rail's Westmoreland Station.

properties.name: Moss Meadows
properties.description: Moss Meadows is a subdivision of about 70 single-family homes dating from the 1970s and 80s adjacent to Harry Moss Park.

properties.name: Kiestwood
properties.description: Established in the 1950s, Kiestwood is a neighborhood of almost 400 homes west of Kiest Park, most of which are original mid-century construction.

properties.name: Kimball
properties.description: Primarily developed during the mid-twentieth century, Kimball is a neighborhood of more than 600 single family homes and apartments west of Kiest Park.

properties.name: Kimball Square
properties.description: Developed in the 1960s by Bill Page, Kimball Square is a neighborhood of approximately 150 single-family homes just south of Kimball High School.

properties.name: Kings Highway
properties.description: Begun as temporary apartment housing for those awaiting construction of their homes in Winnetka Heights, Kings Highway has around 500 homes and was the first conservation district in Dallas, established in 1988.

properties.name: La Bajada
properties.description: La Bajada is a century-old, predominantly Latino neighborhood with almost 300 single family homes near the Margaret Hunt Hill Bridge.

properties.name: La L'aceate
properties.description: La L'aceate is a neighborhood of light industry and warehouses centered on the Union Pacific Railroad with a handful of early-to-mid 20th century houses, including a small collection of shotgun homes.

properties.name: Lake Cliff
properties.description: Centered around the lake of the same name, Lake Cliff was the site of Texas’ largest cultural/amusement complex in the early 1900s. Residential development began in 1913 after the complex closed, and the neighborhood is now a historic district.

properties.name: Lake Forest
properties.description: Lake Forest is a gated community of about 400 residences primarily developed during the late 1990s and early 2000s just south of the LBJ Freeway.

properties.name: RUFCO
properties.description: RUFCO is a small neighborhood in adjacent to Opportunity Park and Oakland Cemetery, composed of multiple additions from the early and mid-twentieth century.

properties.name: Lake Highlands Estates
properties.description: Lake Highlands Estates is a neighborhood of more than 1,500 homes primarily developed during the 1960s just west of the LBJ Freeway.

properties.name: Lake Highlands Square
properties.description: Lake Highlands Square is a small neighborhood of more than 100 homes primarily dating from the 1970s.

properties.name: Lake Highlands North
properties.description: Lake Highlands North is a neighborhood adjacent to the White Rock Trail, made single family homes primarily dating from the 1960s.

properties.name: Lakeland Hills
properties.description: Lakeland Hills is a neighborhood of around 700 homes primarily dating from the 1960s just north of I-30.

properties.name: La Loma
properties.description: La Loma is a small neighborhood of more than 100 homes primarily dating from the 1950s.

properties.name: Lake Park Estates
properties.description: Lake Park Estates is a neighborhood of 288 homes, most dating from the 1950s and ‘60s, located just east of White Rock Lake.

properties.name: Lake Ridge Estates
properties.description: Lake Ridge Estates is a neighborhood northeast of White Rock Lake. Originally developed in the mid-1950s, there are now two neighborhood associations for the original Lake Ridge Estates neighborhood.

properties.name: Lake Ridge Estates North
properties.description: Lake Ridge Estates North is a neighborhood northeast of White Rock Lake. Originally developed in the mid-1950s, there are now two neighborhood associations for the original Lake Ridge Estates neighborhood.

properties.name: Lake West
properties.description: Lake West is a neighborhood of single family homes and apartments which were redeveloped in the early 2000s, located near the Trinity River.

properties.name: Las Haciendas
properties.description: Developed in the mid-1990s, the first new construction in the area in two decades, Las Haciendas is a neighborhood of single-family homes just south of Cockrell Hill.

properties.name: Lakewood Hills or Gastonwood / Coronado Hills
properties.description: Dating back to the 1920s, the neighborhood is comprised of 29 blocks with mostly single-family homes. The neighborhood association was created in 1981.

properties.name: Summit Parc
properties.description: Summit Parc is a subdivision bordering Duncanville of almost 400 homes primarily built around 2000.

properties.name: Grand Park South
properties.description: A Tax Increment Financing District south of Deep Ellum and adjacent to Fair Park. The TIF District aims to redevelop and create a pedestrian friendly mixed-use neighborhood which is in harmony with the area’s historic character, and take full advantage of opportunities for reinvestment created by DART’s expanding light rail system. The district is 228 acres.

properties.name: Lakewood
properties.description: One of many neighborhoods dating from the early- and mid-20th century, Lakewood is located adjacent to White Rock Lake. The Lakewood Neighborhood Association (LNA) is one of the largest homeowners’ associations in the city of Dallas, encompassing about 2,900 residences.

properties.name: Lakewood Heights
properties.description: Developed between 1914 and 1940, Lakewood Heights is located between Lakewood proper and Lower Greenville. About 900 houses are located in the neighborhood, which was placed on Texas’ Most Endangered Places list in 2006 due to the number of teardowns.

properties.name: Lakewood Trails
properties.description: Located just west of White Rock Lake, Lakewood Trails is a neighborhood of about 300 homes developed primarily in the 1950s and 60s. The neighborhood association was formed in 2010, at which time the neighborhood adopted its current name.

properties.name: Lane Park
properties.description: Lane Park is a neighborhood of more than 50 single-family homes and apartments primarily dating from the 1980s just west of the NorthPark Center mall.

properties.name: Willow Falls
properties.description: Willow Falls is a small neighborhood of townhomes and apartments developed around 1970 by the First Wisconsin National Bank of Milwaukee, northwest of Central Expressway and I-635. The neighborhood was marketed as an alternative to apartment-living for young singles. The Willow Falls Clubhouse regularly hosts community meetings.

properties.name: Westhaven
properties.description: Built in the early 1960s by Hallmark Homes, Westhaven is a subdivision of about 500 single family homes just south of Cockrell Hill next to Westhaven and Pecan Grove Parks.

properties.name: Turtle Creek
properties.description: Turtle Creek takes its name from the from the body of water and park that goes through the neighborhood. It is an upscale neighborhood that includes both highrises and some of the most expensive homes in Dallas. The Turtle Creek Association was founded in 1985.

properties.name: Ledbetter
properties.description: Originally the site of the town of Eagle Ford, a Portland Cement company town primarily for Mexican immigrants at the original terminus for the rail lines, Ledbetter is the farthest west neighborhood in Dallas. Eagle Ford was annexed by the City of Dallas in 1953. Neglected over the last 50 years, the neighborhood has seen some improvements in recent decades, particularly due to the neighborhood association, founded in 1984.

properties.name: M Streets or Greenland Hills
properties.description: The M Streets--whose name derives from the fact that the majority of streets in the neighborhood begin with the letter “m”--was founded in 1923, when the McNeny brothers platted and subdivided 98 acres of farmland. Most of the homes date from the 1920s. It is a City of Dallas Conservation District.

properties.name: West End Historic District
properties.description: Turn-of-the-century red brick warehouse district of one- to six-story structures oriented to nearby railroad yards, including governmental, office and light industrial structures representing low-scale, urban, mercantile history of late 19th century Dallas. There has been an increase in residential development in the area of late.

properties.name: Ledbetter Gardens
properties.description: Ledbetter Gardens is a neighborhood of single family homes primarily dating from the 1950s and 70s.

properties.name: Liberty Heights
properties.description: Annexed by Dallas in 1929, Liberty Heights is a small addition of around 200 single-family homes primarily developed during the 1950s and 70s.

properties.name: Linda Heights
properties.description: Linda Heights is a neighborhood of around 300 single-family homes primarily dating from the 1950s near the city limits.

properties.name: Marsalis Park
properties.description: An addition of single family homes built in 1955, Marsalis Park is a neighborhood adjacent to I-35E.

properties.name: Little Forest Hills
properties.description: Adjacent to White Rock Lake and the Dallas Arboretum, Little Forest Hills is a community of homes dating from the 1930s and 40s. Lots were first sold in the 1920s under the original subdivision name of Lakeland Terrace, which was advertised as “across the street from Forest Hills.” The 2007 documentary Subdivided profiles the neighborhood.

properties.name: Lochwood
properties.description: Lochwood is located northeast of White Rock Lake, adjacent to Old Lake Highlands. The neighborhood’s homes date mostly from the 1960s. The homeowners’ association was established in 1984. The neighborhood was formerly known as Dixon Branch.

properties.name: Vista del Cielo
properties.description: Vista del Cielo is a recent subdivision of fewer than one hundred homes located off Loop 12.

properties.name: L.O. Daniel
properties.description: Named for millionaire businessman Lark Owen Daniel who purchased 27 acres just outside Oak Cliff in 1901, L.O. Daniel is a neighborhood of about 180 homes. The Rosemont Crest Historic District, listed on the National Register of Historic Places, is located within the neighborhood.

properties.name: Los Altos
properties.description: Los Altos is a neighborhood of mostly single family homes that primarily date from the mid-twentieth century.

properties.name: Los Encinos
properties.description: Located near Mountain View College, Los Encinos is a neighborhood of single family homes developed for low- and moderate-income families in the mid-1990s.

properties.name: Love Field
properties.description: Love Field is a neighborhood adjacent to Love Field Airport, from which it takes its name, of around 1200 homes and apartments primarily built during the post-war boom.

properties.name: McShann Estates
properties.description: In the 1950s, physician Mansell McShann developed his family’s old farm into a street of 33 sprawling homes for fellow black professionals. The neighborhood has remained an important geography for African-Americans in Dallas for decades.

properties.name: Lower Greenville
properties.description: Prior to the construction of the Central Expressway, Greenville Avenue was the major north-south route from north Dallas to the city center. Primarily developed in the 1920s, Lower Greenville remains an entertainment district in Dallas.

properties.name: Lowest Greenville West
properties.description: Originally a mostly residential neighborhood, Lowest Greenville West first saw major commercial redevelopment around its edges in the 1950s. At the bottom of Greenville Avenue, it is now one of the largest entertainment districts in the city.

properties.name: L Streets
properties.description: Established in 1954, the L Streets is a neighborhood located just two miles northeast of White Rock Lake. The neighborhood association was established in 1994.

properties.name: Main Street District
properties.description: The historic spine of downtown Dallas, the Main Street District has seen thorough revitalization and includes many historic buildings renovated and converted to residential or hotel uses.

properties.name: Maple Lawn
properties.description: A collection of modest, mid-century, single-family homes in Oak Lawn, Maple Lawn shares its name with the elementary school within its boundaries.

properties.name: Wheatley Place
properties.description: Established in 1916 as one of the first planned African American residential neighborhoods, Wheatley Place was named for Phillis Wheatley, an 18th century African American poet. Located southwest of Fair Park, the houses date from 1916 through the 1930s. The neighborhood is a City of Dallas Historic District and listed on the National Register of Historic Places.

properties.name: Abrams-Brookside
properties.description: Abrams-Brookside is a neighborhood of mostly pre-war single-family houses and small apartments and duplexes adjacent to the Lakewood Country Club.

properties.name: Alexander's Village
properties.description: Alexander’s Village is a small, triangular subdivision of approximately 170 single-family homes primarily dating from the 1980s located between the LBJ Freeway and White Rock Lake.

properties.name: Southern Hills
properties.description: Southern Hills is a neighborhood of homes and small apartments dating from the mid-twentieth century onward, located between R.L. Thornton and Marvin D. Love Freeways.

properties.name: Alger Park / Ash Creek
properties.description: Alger Park/Ash Creek is a neighborhood of more than 500 mostly mid-twentieth century homes east of White Rock Lake.

properties.name: American Mount
properties.description: An addition of single-family brick homes that opened and was annexed by the City of Dallas in 1941, American Mount is a neighborhood adjacent to the northern border of Cockrell Hill.

properties.name: Arlington Park
properties.description: Developed in the late 1940s for African American families in response to a housing crisis caused by segregation, Arlington Park is a neighborhood now encompassed by the Southwestern Medical District.

properties.name: Bradford Estates
properties.description: Bradford Estates is a neighborhood of homes and duplexes developed during the 1950s and 60s, north of Love Field and Bachman Lake.

properties.name: Arcadia Park
properties.description: Arcadia Park is a modest, predominantly Hispanic neighborhood just south of I-30 and east of N Walton Walker Boulevard. The neighborhood was developed in the 1920s and incorporated into the city in 1958.

properties.name: Dixon Circle / Sunny Acres
properties.description: Dixon Circle (or Sunny Acres), which was originally built during the early 1900s, is a neighborhood of small single family homes and large government built apartment complexes just north of the Great Trinity Forest.

properties.name: Bishop Arts District
properties.description: Originally developed after the streetcar extended southward to Oak Cliff in 1904, the area saw a resurgence of business and popularity beginning in the mid-1990s. The primarily commercial neighborhood is made up of one to two story brick buildings occupied by restaurants and boutique retail stores.

properties.name: West Kessler
properties.description: Dating from the 1930s, the West Kessler neighborhood consists of about 130 households. The neighborhood, which is adjacent to Stevens Park Golf Course, was formed when the developments of Stevenswood and West Kessler Heights merged in 1982.

properties.name: Baylor / Meadows
properties.description: Located directly north of Deep Ellum, the Baylor/Meadows neighborhood is anchored by Baylor University Medical Center and the Wilson Historic District, where The Meadows Foundation provides office space for non-profits. The neighborhood is a patchwork of development including commercial buildings and converted homes from the early 1900s and a large number of small offices and medical services buildings from the 1960s.

properties.name: Arden Terrace
properties.description: Arden Terrace is a neighborhood located between Five Mile Creek and E Ledbetter Drive with more than 500 homes primarily built during the 1950s and 60s. The neighborhood association was founded in 1995.

properties.name: Spring Creek
properties.description: Dating from the 1960s, Spring Creek is a subdivision of single-family homes bordering Richardson.

properties.name: Dallas Arts District
properties.description: Constructed over the last 30 years, the Dallas Arts District is the largest arts district in the nation, spanning 68 acres and 19 contiguous blocks. Located in the city center, the district includes the Dallas Museum of Art, the Winspear Opera House, the Nasher Sculpture Center and more.

properties.name: Beckley Club Estates
properties.description: Established in the 1920s by developer S.A. Temple, Beckley Club Estates is a subdivision of homes just south of the Dallas Zoo. The homeowners association was established in the early 1980s and resurrected in 2011.

properties.name: Sunset Hill
properties.description: Subdivided from the John Merrifield farm in 1911, Sunset Hills is particularly known for an uncommon type of “California Bungalows” advertised by developers Hann and Kendall in the mid-twentieth century. The neighborhood association was founded in 1990.

properties.name: Swiss Avenue
properties.description: Originally developed in 1905 by R.S. and Collett Munger, the district forms the elegant core of the original 300-acre Munger Place Development. Named by the two Swiss businessmen who originally settled the area in 1859, Swiss Avenue is an excellent example of an intact, early twentieth century residential street of grand homes. The City of Dallas’ first historic district, Swiss Avenue is also listed on the National Register of Historic Places.

properties.name: Bachman
properties.description: Originally its own town, Bachman is a large area located between Love Field and Stemmons Freeway. It has two substantially single-family areas, built in the 1940s and 1950s, interspersed with large garden apartment complexes built in the 1970s. The western portion of the neighborhood is a large warehouse district also built in the 1970s. The neighborhood suffered due to the decline of Love Field’s prominence and a proliferation of strip clubs, which have now closed.

properties.name: Bertrand
properties.description: Bertrand is a neighborhood of mostly small residential homes originally developed in the early 1900s on early Dallas settler Thomas Lagow’s land.

properties.name: St. Andrew's
properties.description: St. Andrew’s is a neighborhood of homes dating primarily from 1950s and 60s, located on the border with Mesquite.

properties.name: Owenwood
properties.description: Owenwood is a neighborhood of approximately 400 homes dating primarily from the 1930s and 50s directly south of I-30.

properties.name: Beckley-Saner
properties.description: Beckley Saner is a neighborhood of almost 200 mostly post-war single-family homes adjacent to Beckley-Saner Park.

properties.name: Beckley Terrace
properties.description: Opened in 1942 as a housing addition for “war production workers,” Beckley Terrace is a small neighborhood east of I-35. The original neighborhood extended westward to Zang Boulevard but was cut off by the construction of the expressway.

properties.name: Beckleywood
properties.description: Beckleywood is a small neighborhood of approximately 60 post-war homes adjacent to I-35E.

properties.name: Belmont
properties.description: The Belmont Addition was founded in 1892, when real estate developer August Belmont, Jr. purchased the land to build one of Dallas’ premier neighborhoods. Today, Belmont is a mix of single-family and multi-family homes at the southern end of Greenville Avenue. It is a City of Dallas Conservation District.

properties.name: Bent Tree North
properties.description: Bent Tree North is a neighborhood east of the Dallas North Tollway, comprised of 632 single-family homes dating from the 1980s and 90s.

properties.name: Bent Tree West
properties.description: Located just to north of the city of Addison, Bent Tree West is a neighborhood of single family homes and apartments developed in the late 1980s.

properties.name: Beverly Hills
properties.description: Platted in 1914 and incorporated into the City of Dallas in 1929, Beverly Hills is a neighborhood located between W Jefferson Boulevard and W Davis Street. The neighborhood association was established in 1997.

properties.name: Tenth Street
properties.description: One of the only remaining intact Freedman’s Towns in the Texas, Tenth Street was adopted as a City of Dallas Historic District in 1993 and is also listed on the National Register of Historic Places. Dating from the post-Civil War era, it is considered the most important African-American neighborhood in southern Dallas.

properties.name: Stevens Park Estates
properties.description: Established in 1926 and named for the original landowner, Stevens Park Estates is a neighborhood of about 200 homes. In 1932, 2029 Mayflower Drive became the first automatic air conditioned house to be offered for sale in Dallas. The neighborhood association was established in 1981.

properties.name: Bluffview
properties.description: Bluffview began in 1924, when developer J.P. Stephenson bought a 215-acre dairy farm and subdivided it into 1-acre parcels. A neighborhood of estates noted for its wooded and hilly terrain it is located between Love Field and the Dallas North Tollway.

properties.name: Casa Linda Estates
properties.description: Carl Brown turned his family farm into what is now known as Casa Linda in 1939, later adding the Casa Linda Plaza shopping center. Today, the neighborhood consists of single family homes, southeast of the intersection of Buckner Boulevard and Garland Road.

properties.name: Bonton
properties.description: A primarily residential neighborhood south of the city center and just north of William Blair Jr. Park- near the confluence of White Rock Creek and the Trinity River. A predominantly African-American neighborhood, it was home to the Turner Courts (or Bonton Projects), built in the mid-1950s, since redeveloped as Buckeye Commons. The neighborhood is also sometimes referred to as Rochester Park.

properties.name: West Ridge Park
properties.description: Part of the city’s multi-million dollar program to build housing for defense workers, West Ridge Park is a neighborhood abutting the northern edge of Cockrell Hill first developed in 1941.

properties.name: Braeburn Glen
properties.description: Established in 1964, Braeburn Glen is a small neighborhood homes directly west of the Dallas Athletic Club & Golf Course, near the border with Mesquite.

properties.name: Trinity Heights or Brentwood
properties.description: Originally its own city, Trinity Heights was annexed in 1923 by the City of Dallas, the largest single addition since Oak Cliff was annexed. This area was developed beginning in the 1930s and is located just west of the Cedar Crest Golf Course.

properties.name: Briarwood
properties.description: Briarwood is a neighborhood of about 700 single-family homes established in 1978 just west of I-635. The neighborhood association was formed in 1981.

properties.name: Cadillac Heights
properties.description: A neighborhood of around 70 homes on the western edge of the Trinity River at Cedar Crest Boulevard, Cadillac Heights was originally named Roosevelt Heights when developed in the 1930s. The neighborhood is now at the center of a number of controversies: poisoning of residents by factories, flooding from the Trinity River and planned development that would demolish the neighborhood.

properties.name: Brookshire Park
properties.description: Brookshire Park is a neighborhood of homes and duplexes dating primarily from the 1960s and 70s in northern Dallas just west of the Central Expressway. The neighborhood association was founded in 1971.

properties.name: Bryan Place
properties.description: Bryan Place, located just east of the city center, was built in the early 1980s by developer Fox & Jacobs. Bryan Place was one of the first in-town East Dallas neighborhoods in a half-century of mass suburbanization.

properties.name: Stevens Park Village
properties.description: First developed between 1939 and 1941, with an addition built on the west in the 1950s, Stevens Park Village is located on the edge of a cliff. The neighborhood association was formed in 1991.

properties.name: Buckner Terrace
properties.description: Buckner Terrace is a large neighborhood located just south of I-30. It has about 4,000 homes and apartment complexes in a variety of sizes primarily built in the 1970s and 80s.

properties.name: Cambridge Place
properties.description: Cambridge Place is a gated community of large brick and stone homes built between 1995 and 2007 to the eeast of the Preston Trail Golf Club.

properties.name: Vista Real
properties.description: Vista Real is a neighborhood adjacent to Mountain View College. While some development started in the 1950s, the majority of homes and apartments in the neighborhood were built in the late 1990s.

properties.name: Campbell Green
properties.description: Developed in the 1970s, Campbell Green is a neighborhood that straddles Campbell Road and includes Campbell Green Park. The neighborhood association, formed in 1973, was originally called the Tioga Preston Association; the name was changed in 2011.

properties.name: Caruth Hills
properties.description: Possibly the only neighborhood of its kind in Dallas, Caruth Hills spans both the city of Dallas and University Park. It is a neighborhood of 1,325 single-family homes located on the original homestead of William Barr Caruth. Though some homes in the neighborhood date from the 1940s and 1950s, many have been more recently rebuilt.

properties.name: Caruth Terrace
properties.description: Developed by William Walter Caruth, Jr. and with lots first sold in 1949, Caruth Terrace is a neighborhood of around 450 homes and apartments just east of the Park Cities.

properties.name: Casa Linda Forest
properties.description: Casa Linda Forest is a neighborhood of five subdivisions, comprising about 600 homes primarily developed in the 1950s and 60s, southeast of White Rock Lake.

properties.name: Casa View
properties.description: First developed in the 1950s, Casa View is one of the neighborhoods in the Casa View/Casa Linda area in East Dallas that stretches to the border of Mesquite. It is bordered by a substantial Kansas City Southern Railway facility on the north.

properties.name: Casa View Haven
properties.description: Casa View Haven is a neighborhood of about 1,000 brick homes off Ferguson Road built primarily in the 1950s. The neighborhood association was formed in 2009.

properties.name: Casa View Oaks
properties.description: Established in 1954, Casa View Oaks is a neighborhood of ranch homes east of White Rock Lake. It has the largest collection of homes designed by Cliff May, the “father of the California ranch house” in Dallas.

properties.name: Cedar Creek Ranch
properties.description: Cedar Creek Ranch is a mixed-income development of single-family homes constructed in the late 2000s at the city’s southern limit.

properties.name: Cedar Crest
properties.description: Developed beginning in 1923 by the Forest Avenue Development Company, Cedar Crest is a neighborhood adjacent to the Cedar Crest Golf Course with about 450 homes, most dating from the 1950s and 60s. The neighborhood association was founded in 1961.

properties.name: North Stonewall Terrace
properties.description: Just north of the Stonewall Jackson Elementary School, from which the neighborhood takes its name, Stonewall Terrace was established in 1939 and developed by W.W. Caruth, Jr. An expansion to the addition, North Stonewall Terrace, was announced in 1941.

properties.name: Cedar Haven
properties.description: Developed beginning in the 1930s, Cedar Haven is a mix of brick and woodframe single-family homes near the Dallas Zoo.

properties.name: Cedar Crest Country Club Estates
properties.description: Developed in the 1950s by the father-son Tips Company adjacent to the Cedar Crest Golf Course, the Dallas Morning News described the hilltop neighborhood as “universally recognized as one of the most beautiful in the city of Dallas.”

properties.name: Cigarette Hill
properties.description: Also known as Alameda Heights and Carver Heights, Cigarette Hill is a predominantly African-American neighborhood just south of S Lancaster Road. It is rural in character, and comprised of modest single-family homes. Established in 1977 and in the center of the neighborhood, the Alameda Heights Community Outreach Center is an important local asset. Cigarette Hill is a Neighborhood Investment Program target area and in the Lancaster Corridor Tax Increment Financing District.

properties.name: The Bottoms
properties.description: Named for its position in the flood-prone bottom lands of the Trinity River, The Bottoms is a small, historically African American neighborhood comprised of approximately 120 single family homes and duplexes originally built in the early twentieth century just north of the Tenth Street Historic District. The two neighborhoods are often referred to together.

properties.name: Twin Oaks
properties.description: Twin Oaks is a neighborhood of single family homes primarily developed during the 1960s to the east of the Dallas Executive Airport.

properties.name: Cedar Crest Village
properties.description: Cedar Crest Village is a 100-acre neighborhood developed as an all-brick addition adjacent to the Cedar Crest Country Club in the post-war era.

properties.name: Cedar Oaks
properties.description: Originally developed during the late 1930s, Cedar Oaks is a neighborhood of about 250 homes just south of the Dallas Zoo.

properties.name: Cochran Heights
properties.description: Adjacent to the Central Expressway, many of the homes in the Cochran Heights neighborhood were built by the same architect, Charles Dilbeck, in the 1930s and 40s.

properties.name: Cityplace
properties.description: A Tax Increment Financing district created in 1992 to encourage dense, mixed-use development just north of the city center, Cityplace straddles the Central Expressway and overlaps with a number of adjacent neighborhoods.

properties.name: West Village
properties.description: West Village is a new mixed-use development located in the center of Uptown. Since it opened in 2001, it has doubled in size.

properties.name: Windsor Park
properties.description: Windsor Park is a neighborhood of approximately 350 single family homes primarily built in 1960s just north of the Park Cities on the other side of Central Expressway from The Shops at Park Lane.

properties.name: Cedars
properties.description: Located directly south of the city center, the Cedars is one of Dallas’s oldest neighborhoods, mainly comprising of recently converted warehouses originally built in the late 1800s and early 1900s. The neighborhood association was founded in 2003.

properties.name: Cedar Vista
properties.description: Cedar Vista is a neighborhood of homes and apartments primarily built in the early 2000s just north of I-20.

properties.name: Civic Center District
properties.description: The Civic Center District, on the south end of the city center, includes the Dallas City Hall, the Central Library and the Convention Center. It is mainly compromised of large civic and business buildings, dating from the early to mid 1900s.

properties.name: Crestview Park
properties.description: Crestview Park is a small neighborhood of about 100 homes dating from the 1950s.

properties.name: Chalfont Place
properties.description: Chalfont Place is a large neighborhood of around 3000 apartments developed in the 1970s and 80s on the western edge of the city limits.

properties.name: Chapel Downs
properties.description: A 120-acre subdivision adjacent to Sparkman Club Estates in northwest Dallas, Chapel Downs was developed in the early 1960s. The planned community included custom homes, a swimming pool and a community center. Chapel Downs was an original member of the Dallas Homeowner’s League.

properties.name: Colony Square
properties.description: Built as an “upscale adult” condominium community in the 1960s, Colony Square is a gated neighborhood just north of Calvary Hill Cemetary

properties.name: Chimney Hill
properties.description: Established in the 1970s, Chimney Hill is a neighborhood of homes and apartments mostly developed during the 1970s and 80s, located directly west of Richland College.

properties.name: Claremont Addition
properties.description: The Claremont Addition is an enclave of about 600 brick homes between Ferguson Road and I-30 built in the late 1950s and early 1960s.

properties.name: Wheatland Hills
properties.description: Wheatland Hills is a neighborhood of residential homes and apartments mainly built in early 2000s located just north of I-20.

properties.name: Colonial Hill
properties.description: The oldest of the South Dallas Historic Districts, Colonial Hill illustrates a classic suburban streetcar pattern. Developed after the streetcar extended southward in 1888 and made up of twenty separate additions, many of the earlier parts of the neighborhood were destroyed by the construction of I-45 and Central Expressway.

properties.name: The Cloisters
properties.description: Developed in the 1960s on a peninsula of White Rock Lake, The Cloisters is a neighborhood of about 100 homes.

properties.name: Club Oaks
properties.description: A mid-century subdivision located just off Marvin D. Love Freeway, homeowners in Club Oaks protested the rezoning of an adjacent tract of land for the Redbird Airport in 1959-60.

properties.name: Wind Ridge Estates
properties.description: Wind Ridge Estates is a subdivision of single family homes primarily built in the early 2000s located in the wooded southwestern corner of Dallas near Joe Pool Lake.

properties.name: Cochran Chapel
properties.description: Named for the Methodist church that sits just to its north, Cochran Chapel is a neighborhood of just one 1.1-mile street located next to the Bachman Creek Nature Trail and just west of Love Field.

properties.name: Commercial Center
properties.description: The Commercial Center includes a significant portion of the DART rail’s downtown transit mall and surrounding structures. It is compromised of mainly of office, hotel and residential skycrapers, with around 500 multi-family units.

properties.name: Copperfield
properties.description: Copperfield is a planned neighborhood of townhomes and condominiums primarily dating from the 1970s and 80s just south of LBJ Freeway.

properties.name: Country Creek
properties.description: Country Creek is a neighborhood of townhomes and apartments near Mountain Creek Lake. The neighborhood is also home to the headquarters of the Army & Air Force Exchange Services.

properties.name: Disney Streets
properties.description: Developed in the 1950s, streets in the neighborhood were named after Walt Disney characters and places. The neighborhood, which is compromised of about 300 homes, applied to be a conservation district but was denied.

properties.name: Country Forest / Jackson Meadows
properties.description: Developed in the late 1970s, Country Forest/Jackson Meadows is a neighborhood of single family homes adjacent to Richland College.

properties.name: Winnetka Heights
properties.description: Originally platted in 1908, Winnetka Heights is the most intact of the early twentieth century neighborhoods of Oak Cliff. The neighborhood is the largest historic district in Dallas, adopted to the city’s registry in 1981, and is also listed on the National Register of Historic Places. The neighborhood has over 800 homes, a mix of single- and multi-family units.

properties.name: Oak Cliff Gardens
properties.description: Adjacent to the VA Hospital, Oak Cliff Gardens is a neighborhood that was subdivided into tracts in the 1930s and annexed into the city in 1943. Recently, Habitat for Humanity has been building in the neighborhood, specifically with the goal to help veterans become homeowners.

properties.name: Dallas Land & Loan
properties.description: The Dallas Land & Loan neighborhood is the remaining area of land developed by Thomas Marsalis as three Dallas Land Loan Additions in the late nineteenth century. It contains the largest collection of turn-of-the-century Victorian homes in Dallas. New planning ordinances, approved in August 2010, would change the name of this area to the Garden District and allow for increased development.

properties.name: Design District
properties.description: Developed in the last 50 years, the Design District is an arts, antiques, gallery and commercial warehouse district just west of the city center. The neighborhood was originally developed as part of the Trinity Industrial District on land reclaimed from the Trinity River floodplain after construction of the levee system.

properties.name: Wisdom Terrace
properties.description: Wisdom Terrace is a neighborhood of affordable homes, first developed in 2000 by NuHome Designs, near the I-35 and I-20 junction.

properties.name: The Heights
properties.description: Often grouped with The Bottoms and the Tenth Street Historic District, The Heights is on a hilltop overlooking downtown with homes dating from the 1930s.

properties.name: Deep Ellum
properties.description: An arts and entertainment district directly east of downtown, the neighborhood was historically a commercial district for African-Americans and home to a flourishing blues and jazz scene in the early twentieth century.

properties.name: The Dells District
properties.description: First developed as the Irwindell Addition in the late 1920s on a former dairy farm, The Dells neighborhood is a small pocket of brick and stone cottages.

properties.name: Druid Hills
properties.description: Druid Hills is a neighborhood of single family homes and apartments primarily dating from the 1960s.

properties.name: The Meadows
properties.description: Dating from the 1960s, The Meadows is a residential neighborhood built on top of the former Glen Lakes Golf Course. The neighborhood association has been in existence since the 1970s.

properties.name: Devonshire
properties.description: Devonshire is a neighborhood of approximately 700 homes primarily built during the 1940s directly west of University Park.

properties.name: Dolphin Heights
properties.description: Dolphin Heights is located south of Interstate 30 and east of Fair Park. The neighborhood association was founded in 2004 to combat crime and neighborhood decline. Two historic cemeteries, the Beeman Cemetery and Shearith Israel Cemetery, are within its boundaries.

properties.name: East Garrett Park
properties.description: East Garrett Park is a small neighborhood bordering the Swiss Avenue Historic District. In response to rising crime in the 1980s, Dallas Habitat for Humanity built or renovated dozens of houses in the neighborhood and SMU created the Inter-Community Experience (ICE) House on Bryan Parkway.

properties.name: East Kessler Park
properties.description: Established in 1937 and the easternmost of the “Kessler neighborhoods,” East Kessler Park is located just south of I-30 and west of the Trinity. The neighborhood association was founded in 1950.

properties.name: Eastwood Estates
properties.description: Eastwood Estates is a neighborhood of about 400 homes developed in the 1990s just east of White Rock Lake.

properties.name: Eastwood Hills
properties.description: Developed beginning in the 1960s, Eastwood Hills is east of White Rock Lake and north of I-30. The neighborhood association was founded in 2008.

properties.name: Edgemont Park
properties.description: A very small neighborhood of single-family homes along seven blocks of Prospect Avenue, Edgemont Park was first platted in 1917. Today there are 55 houses in the neighborhood, which was granted conservation district status in 2006.

properties.name: Edgewood Place
properties.description: A turn of the century addition to the city, intending to keep up with development spurred by the Houston & Texas Central railroad, Edgewood Place is a historically African American community.

properties.name: Enclave at White Rock
properties.description: Enclave at White Rock is a planned neighborhood of homes developed in the late 1990s, just south of White Rock Lake.

properties.name: Elm Thicket or North Park
properties.description: Elm Thicket, also sometimes referred to as North Park, is a neighborhood adjacent to Love Field primarily developed in the post-war housing boom. There are more than 2300 homes and apartments in the historically African American neighborhood.

properties.name: Glencoe Park
properties.description: Glencoe Park is a neighborhood adjacent to the Central Expressway. Primarily developed in the 1940s and 50s, the neighborhood is a mixture of single-family homes, duplexes and small apartment buildlings. The neighborhood has experienced a recent surge in redevelopment.

properties.name: Enclave at Ash Creek
properties.description: Enclave at Ash Creek is a gated community of 66 homes just southeast of White Rock Lake.

properties.name: Wilshire Heights
properties.description: Wilshire Heights is a neighborhood of single family homes first developed in the 1930s, located directly west of Lakewood and north of Lakewood Heights.

properties.name: Whispering Hills
properties.description: Whispering Hills is a neighborhood of single family homes primarily developed in the 1970s located in the far northeast corner of Dallas, adjacent to Richardson.

properties.name: Elmwood
properties.description: Elmwood was developed in the 1920s through 1950s on the land of a former dairy farm. The current neighborhood association was formed in 2000, replacing the original 1982 association.

properties.name: El Tivoli Place
properties.description: Named for the country club that originally occupied the site and first developed for Navy personnel returning from World War II, El Tivoli Place is a neighborhood north of W Davis St. The neighborhood association was founded in 1986 to combat a perceived decline in the neighborhood.

properties.name: Estates of Avalon
properties.description: A small subdivision of luxury homes, Estates of Avalon is located just north of Preston Hollow.

properties.name: Estates West
properties.description: Established in the 1960s, Estates West is a neighborhood of almost 700 homes and apartments adjacent to the eastern city limits between I-635 and President George Bush Turnpike.

properties.name: Exline / Charles Rice
properties.description: Located south of Fair Park, Exline is a neighborhood of pre-war homes that gained notoriety in the 1950s for a series of bombings on African American homeowners. Today, the neighborhood centers on the Park South YMCA and Exline Park and Recreation Center, which includes the first public pool open to African Americans in the city.

properties.name: Exposition Park
properties.description: Located between Deep Ellum and Fair Park, Exposition Park’s name derives from its location on the doorstep of the Texas State Fair and Dallas Exposition. Currently, early 20th century industrial buildings are undergoing adaptive re-use, as the neighborhood crafts an identity as an artistic and creative community.

properties.name: Farmers Market District
properties.description: Gaining its name from the year-round Dallas Farmers Market, established in 1939 and centered at Pearl and Cadiz Streets, the Farmers Market District in the southeastern corner of the city center is now seeing residential development.

properties.name: Forest Hills
properties.description: Forest Hills is a neighborhood of approximately 900 large homes primarily dating from the 1950s and 90s adjacent to White Rock Lake.

properties.name: Mill City
properties.description: Named for the twine and cotton mill, owned and run by African-Americans, that operated in the area in the early twentieth century, Mill City is a neighborhood adjacent to Fair Park.

properties.name: Fitzhugh / Capitol
properties.description: Originally developed in the early 1900s, Fitzhugh/Capitol is a predominantly Hispanic neighborhood of more than 4000 homes and apartments.

properties.name: Glen Lakes
properties.description: Glen Lakes is a subdivision of homes and apartments built primarily during the 1980s just north of University Park and adjacent to the Central Expressway.

properties.name: Five Mile Creek
properties.description: Named for the creek that runs through it, Five Mile Creek is a neighborhood comprised of around 1400 homes primarily dating from the 1950s and 60s.

properties.name: Forest Heights
properties.description: Also known as “The Triangle,” Forest Heights is a neighborhood just one mile south of the city center. The Forest Heights NDC was created in 1994 to combat blight and crime.

properties.name: Glen Meadow Estates
properties.description: Established in 1961, Glen Meadow Estates is a neighborhood of 1,100 homes.

properties.name: Beckley Heights
properties.description: Beckley Heights is a neighborhood of over 600 single-family homes west of I-35. The neighborhood was developed in the post-war era and advertised as “moderately priced frame homes” approved for GI Bill loans. The area was annexed to the City of Dallas in 1951.

properties.name: Hillcrest Manor
properties.description: Hillcrest Manor is a neighborhood of almost 300 homes primarily dating from the 1970s.

properties.name: Forest Meade
properties.description: Forest Meade is a neighborhood developed during the 1970s just south of White Rock Lake.

properties.name: Forest Meadow
properties.description: Forest Meadow is a small neighborhood of subdivisions with approximately 500 homes developed during the 1970s and 80s just south of the LBJ Freeway. The crime patrol was founded in 1979.

properties.name: Forest Oaks
properties.description: Forest Oaks is a neighborhood of approximately 60 homes primarily dating from the 1950s and 60s located between I-30 and White Rock Lake.

properties.name: Fox Hollow
properties.description: Fox Hollow is a subdivision of 235 homes dating from the 1970s near Joe Pool Lake.

properties.name: The Village
properties.description: Originally developed in the 1960s and ‘70s, The Village is a group of 17 apartment communities with about 10,000 residents. The complex is just east of the Central Expressway, and covers about 307 acres.

properties.name: Town Creek
properties.description: Town Creek is a subdivision just south of the LBJ Freeway. The homeowners association was founded in 1976.

properties.name: Woodland Canyon
properties.description: Woodland Canyon is a neighborhood of about 250 single-family homes developed in the 1960s by M.L. Merrick, near The Golf Club of Dallas.

properties.name: Frazier
properties.description: With most homes built in the 1920s and 30s, Frazier, like much of south Dallas, became predominantly African American following WWII. Located just east of Fair Park, the neighborhood is named in honor of Julia Caldwell Frazier, the first African American woman to serve as a high school principal in Dallas. The 1,100-acre neighborhood has lost two-thirds of its population in the last three decades.

properties.name: Oakdale
properties.description: Oakdale is a neighborhood of about 200 homes, built between 1990 and 2001, just south of the President George Bush Turnpike.

properties.name: Fruitdale
properties.description: Incorporated as its own city in 1937 and annexed by the City of Dallas in 1964, development in Fruitdale increased after WWII but it has remained relatively rural. The community organization was formed in 1967.

properties.name: Glen Oaks
properties.description: Developed between 1952 and 1967 on the former Frank Holland Farm, Glen Oaks is a neighborhood of single family homes located between US-67 and I-35.

properties.name: Glenview
properties.description: Glenview is a neighborhood of predominantly mid-century single-family homes near the intersection of Ledbetter Drive and I-35.

properties.name: Greenleaf Village
properties.description: A partnership between the Dallas Housing Authority and a number of non-profits, Greenleaf Village is a neighborhood of single-family homes that addresses the persistent local shortage of quality, affordable housing.

properties.name: Greenway Parks
properties.description: Greenway Parks, located just west of Highland Park, was founded in 1927 in an English commons tradition. It is a City of Dallas Conservation District.

properties.name: Harbor Glen
properties.description: Harbor Glen is a small subidivision of single family homes developed in the 2000s northeast of Joe Pool Lake.

properties.name: Hamilton Park
properties.description: Founded in 1954, Hamilton Park was a pioneering subdivision, intended specifically for middle-class black families in then-segregated Dallas. It remains a predominantly, although not exclusively, black community with significant historic preservation efforts.

properties.name: Hampton Hills
properties.description: Hampton Hills is a neighborhood that was established in 1924 along the Oak Cliff streetcar line. The neighborhood association was formed in 1990.

properties.name: Harbord Oaks Estates
properties.description: Harbord Oaks Estates is a neighborhood of about 30 homes built in the late 1980s.

properties.name: Henderson
properties.description: First developed in the early 1900s, Henderson is a neighborhood of single family homes and apartments just east of Central Expressway that is undergoing redevelopment.

properties.name: Hidden Valley
properties.description: Established in 1959, Hidden Valley is a neighborhood of single-family brick homes.

properties.name: High Hollows
properties.description: Developed in the early 1970s, High Hollows is composed of 2-story condominium buildings and townhomes just west of the Central Expressway.
